I"P<p>In the previous section, we introduced the Fourier tranform and how to interpret it. In this section, we introduce some properties of the Fourier transform that allow us to simplify calculations significantly. This will allow us to easily compute Fourier transforms of more complicated functions, as well as pave the way to solving differential equations.</p>

<p>We recall the definition of the Fourier transform:</p>

<script type="math/tex; mode=display">\mathcal{F}(f)(k) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}}\int_{-\infty}^\infty e^{-ikx} f(x) dx.</script>

<div class="result">
<p> <b>Properties of the Fourier Transform</b> </p>
<p> Let $f(x)$ and $g(x)$ be functions, $\lambda$ any complex scalar, and $f^{(n)}(x) = \frac{d^n f}{dx^n}$ denote the $n$-th derivative of the function $f$. Then the following hold.
  </p>
<ol>
<li>Linearity
  $$\mathcal{F}(f+g) = \mathcal{F}(f) + \mathcal{F}(g)$$</li>  
<li>Scalar Multiplication 
  $$\mathcal{F}(\lambda f) = \lambda\mathcal{F}(f).$$ </li>
<li>Shifting of Argument in $x$ space
  $$\mathcal{F}(f(x-a)) = e^{iak}\mathcal{F}(f) </li>
<li>Shifting of Argument in $k$ space
$$\mathcal{F}(e^{iax}f(x)) = \mathcal{F}(f)(x-a) </li>
<li>Fourier Transform of Derivatives:
  $$\mathcal{F}(f^{(n)}) = (-ik)^n\mathcal{F}(f)$$ </li>
<li>Fourier Transform of Powers of $x^n$ times $f$:
  $$\mathcal{F}(x^n f)(k) = \frac{1}{(-1)^n} \frac{d^n}{dk^n}\mathcal{F}(f)(k)$$ </li>
</ol>

</div>

<p>These properties can be shown by direct computation. Before we proceed, letâ€™s do a few examples.</p>

